DeepMetal: An Intelligent Metal Recommendation System¶

TDI Capstone Proposal¶

Alexander Sack¶

November 2018¶

Powered by¶

Why DeepMetal?¶

  • Combine my passion for music with my one for data science
    • I'm a co-founder of the website Metal-Fi and a guest writer for the blog Angry Metal-Guy, one the most popular metal sites on the web with over a million views per month.
  • Leverage state-of-the-art deep learning and NLP frameworks to build a robust sentiment analysis classifier
  • Questions that need answers:
    • Which subgenre of metal garners the most favorable reviews?
    • Given my favorite metal band is X, what new album should I be listening to?
    • Do bands with more released albums get better or worse over time?
    • Can we predict the rating of a new review based on prior reviews?

Case Study: "Angry Metal-AI"¶

  • Angry Metal Guy is a reviewed based blog where new metal records are scored by its writing staff on a five point scale in half point increments.
  • Built multiple sentiment analysis classifiers using Naive Bayes (sklearn) and RNNs (Keras/Tensorflow, GloVE/word2vec embeddings)
  • Demonstrate my ability to apply modern data science techniques on a real world dataset

In [109]:
# Multi reviews are terribly indexed (read: not indexed) on AMG. A multi review is a review
# that contains two or more embedded reviews/ratings for a particular release.
#
# What we do here is for each multi review, we take the arithmetic mean of the embedded reviews
# as the final rating score. This obviously has the by product of mincing words between authors but
# that's OK since our model is meant to be author agnostic.
ratings = []
for i in df.index:
    words = df.loc[i, 'review'].split()
    matches = re.findall(r'.*(Rating:|Rating [-|]|Score:)(.*)\s*', df.loc[i, 'review'])
    if len(matches) > 1:
        ratings = []
        for match in matches:
            mobj = re.search(r'\s*(\d(\.\d+)?)(\/(\d+(\.\d)?))?', match[1])
            if mobj:
                ratings.append(mobj.group(1))
        if len(ratings) > 1:
            mean = np.mean(list(map(float, ratings)))
            print(i, df.loc[i, 'title'], ratings, mean)
            df.loc[i, 'rating'] = mean

# Technically speaking, AMG's ratings are matched to certain words:
#
# Rating System
# 5.0 - Perfect
# 4.5 - Excellent
# 4.0 - Great
# 3.5 - Very Good
# 3.0 - Good
# 2.5 - Mixed
# 2.0 - Disappointing
# 1.5 - Bad
# 1.0 - Embarrassing
# 0.5 - Pathetic
# 0.0 - Worthless
#
# Let's do another pass but this time convert the rating word)(s) to a score
word2rating = {
                'Perfect' : 5.0,
                'Excellent': 4.5,
                'Great': 4.0,
                'Very Good': 3.5,
                'Good': 3.0,
                'Mixed': 2.5,
                'Disappointing': 2.0,
                'Bad': 1.5,
                'Embarrassing': 1.0,
                'Pathetic': 0.5,
                'Worthless': 0.0
}

for unrated in unrated_indexes:
    mobj = re.search(r'.*(Rating:|Rating [-|]|Score:)(.*)\s*', df.loc[unrated, 'review'])
    if mobj:
        # Remember that we are filtering UTF-8 encoded strings so normalize
        # before casefolding below.
        wordRating = unicodedata.normalize('NFKD', mobj.group(2)).strip()
        wordRating = wordRating.strip('!')
        if unrated == 1982:
            r1982 = wordRating
        foundRating = False
        for key, value in word2rating.items():
            if key.casefold() == wordRating.casefold():
                df.loc[unrated, 'rating'] = value
                foundRating = True
                break
        if not foundRating:
            print(unrated, wordRating)

# Now extract the words from the reviews, remove stop words and stem.
def review2words(review, stem=True):
    regex = re.compile('[^a-zA-Z]')
    text = regex.sub(' ', review)
    words = text.lower().strip().split()
    words = [word for word in words if word not in stopwords.words('english')]
    if stem:
        words = [stemmer.stem(word) for word in words]

    return " ".join(words)
df['words'] = df['review'].apply(review2words)
df['words_cnt'] = df['words'].apply(lambda x: len(x.split(' ')))

In [131]:
def prepare_amg_data(data):
    """Prepare training and test sets from AMG reviews."""
    
    data_train = data['train']['pos']+data['train']['neg']
    data_test = data['test']['pos']+data['test']['neg']
    labels_train = [1]*len(data['train']['pos'])+[0]*len(data['train']['neg'])
    labels_test = [1]*len(data['test']['pos'])+[0]*len(data['test']['neg'])
    data_train, labels_train = shuffle(data_train, labels_train)
    data_test, labels_test = shuffle(data_test, labels_test)
    
    # Return a unified training data, test data, training labels, test labets
    return data_train, data_test, labels_train, labels_test

data_train, data_test, labels_train, labels_test = prepare_amg_data(data)
print("AMG reviews (combined): train = {}, test = {}".format(len(data_train), len(data_test)))

AMG reviews (combined): train = 2602, test = 650

--- Raw review ---
Pulling off a long song  be it a ten-minute black metal piece or an hour-plus funeral doom opus  takes very deliberate pacing. Great drone and doom bands know this and know how to pull the listener rather than push them. If the song moves too fast, it can seem to lose structure, but if it moves too slowly, it can stagnate and sour the listener to its next idea. One has to have the pacing and space to keep themselves involved.Sunn O)))will keep you guessing at when they'll place the next chord, and they use the naturally nuanced texture of high-amplification to fill the space between.Bell Witch can stretch a two-note riff out for the length of a grindcore album just by pinching each note out of the bass with gravitas.
Yhdarl have spent a decade writing monstrous songs; the formerly one-man, currently one-man-one-woman, depressive black/drone/doom project claims dozens of EPs, demos, and LPs since 2007, and this year'sLoss LP seems to be a big investment for them. Such a large investment, in fact, that frontman and multi-instrumentalistDh (of Clouds and about seventy other bands)released a two-part album last year to help cover the cost ofLoss's physical release. An album which, I don't mind telling you, clocks in at five hours long.Yhdarlmake big, big music.
Loss by YHDARL
Loss's most immediate strength reveals itself within the album's first seconds. "Ignite-Ashes" opens with a string scrape and a shriek so raw and impassioned that the first riff nearly drowns beneath it. BetweenDh, his blackened buddy Larvalis and a bevy of guest spots, this album covers nearly every corner of the black metal vocal range and the first few moments of "Ignite - Ashes" provide a tantalizing taste of even broader vocal variety to come.
That variety largely carries the album through its roughest spots, where the three enormous songs occasionally drag. "Ignite - Ashes" subsists on blast beats and simple trem-picked patterns for ten minutes beforeYhdarl deign to pull back and add quiet contrast, and after eight minutes of great vocals and lackluster guitar work, I was ready to write off this album as a casualty of excess. Yet, better late than never, the song recovers in its last third. Much to my surprise, the twenty minute "Despise - Pity" fares quite well, and shifts through a plethora of compelling passages, balancing repetition and novelty remarkably well. The cleanly sung lines that enter around eleven minutes in come as a pleasant surprise, recalling the fragility ofOathbreaker just before huge power chords fracture the atmosphere.

Like any songs of this length, it's possible to pick apart the composition and suggest trimming repetitions or excising a weaker idea to move the song along faster, butYhdarl's talent at arranging largely obviates the need for big changes. I'll check my watch if I'm not in the mood for depressive blackened doom, but when the music fits my mood,Loss proves itself more than worthy of my attention. It takes a lot of patience to uncover the album's best moments, but when caught in its current, I find myself pulled along just as I should be.
I don't loveLoss, but it has proven far better than I could have expected; an expansive and depressive journey that I expect to still enjoy when I'm in the mood, and at under fifty minutes long, it's a much smaller commitment thanCloak of Ash,Sisterre, andMirror Reaper, a few of my other go-to albums for long and encapsulating soundscapes. For those often moved by depressive black metal and long-form doom,Yhdarl's efforts here will be welcome.

# Alright, now let's frame the problem as both a binary and multi-classification problem with each rating being
# either a sentiment or discrete category (we should have 11 categories from 0-5 in half increments).
#
# Then we will build RNN networks to predict sentiment as well as the ratings.

# Setup all labels and review text, one-hot encode the category codes

maxlen = 300
training_samples = 2500
validation_samples = 500
max_words = 1000

tokenizer = Tokenizer(num_words=max_words)
tokenizer.fit_on_texts(texts)
sequences = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(texts)

word_index = tokenizer.word_index
data = pad_sequences(sequences, maxlen=maxlen)

# We will shuffle indexes randomly and then split into
# training, validation, and test sets respectively.
indices = np.arange(data.shape[0])
np.random.shuffle(indices)
data = data[indices]
labels = labels[indices]
sent_labels = sent_labels[indices]

# Train
x_train = data[:training_samples]
y_train = labels[:training_samples]
y_sent_train = sent_labels[:training_samples]

# Validation
x_val = data[training_samples: training_samples + validation_samples]
y_val = labels[training_samples: training_samples + validation_samples]
y_sent_val = sent_labels[training_samples: training_samples + validation_samples]

# Test
x_test = data[training_samples + validation_samples:]
y_test = labels[training_samples + validation_samples:]
y_sent_test = sent_labels[training_samples + validation_samples:]

# Let's use a GLoVE embedding since we don't have a lot of data to build our own embedding layer
data_dir = 'data'
glove_dir = os.path.join(data_dir, 'glove6B')
if not os.path.exists(glove_dir):
    os.mkdir(glove_dir)
glove_file = os.path.join(glove_dir, 'glove.6B.zip')
url = 'http://nlp.stanford.edu/data/glove.6B.zip'
if not os.path.exists(glove_file):
    print("Downloading {0}...".format(url), end="")
    urllib.request.urlretrieve(url, glove_file)
    print("done")
    print("Extracting...", end="")
    glove_zip = zipfile.ZipFile(glove_file, 'r')
    glove_zip.extractall(glove_dir)
    glove_zip.close()
    print("done")
else:
    print("glove6B already installed...")

embeddings_dim = 300
embeddings_index = {}
embeddings_matrix = np.zeros((max_words, embeddings_dim))
with open(os.path.join(glove_dir, 'glove.6B.300d.txt'), encoding='utf-8') as f:
    for line in f:
        values = line.split()
        word = values[0]
        coefs = np.asarray(values[1:], dtype='float32')
        embeddings_index[word] = coefs
In [150]:
# Generic function to graph accuracy and loss of various different models
def graph_model(history):
    acc = history.history['acc']
    val_acc = history.history['val_acc']
    loss = history.history['loss']
    val_loss = history.history['val_loss']
    epochs = range(1, len(acc) + 1)

    plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
    plt.plot(epochs, acc, 'bo', label='Training acc')
    plt.plot(epochs, val_acc, 'b', label='Validation acc')
    plt.title('Training and validation accuracy')
    plt.legend()
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))

    plt.plot(epochs, loss, 'bo', label='Training loss')
    plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, 'b', label='Validation loss')
    plt.title('Training and validation loss')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

# Sentiment analysis with GLoVE embeddings
model = Sequential()
model.add(Embedding(max_words, embeddings_dim, input_length=maxlen))
model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
model.summary()
# Use GLoVE embeddings instead of trying to learn them on the fly
model.layers[0].set_weights([embeddings_matrix])
model.layers[0].trainable = False
model.compile(optimizer='rmsprop',
              loss='binary_crossentropy',
              metrics=['acc'])
history = model.fit(x_train, y_sent_train,
                    epochs=10,
                    batch_size=32,
                    validation_data=(x_val, y_sent_val))
model.save_weights('data/pre_trained_sent_glove_model.h5')
model.evaluate(x_test, y_sent_test)

Key Takeaways¶

  • Data, data, and moar data
    • The Metal-Archives is the largest repository of metal reviews on the web with a total of ~1 million approved reviews for 47069 unique albums (11/8/2018).
    • Open-sourced the Metal-Archives Query (maq) tool on GitHub
  • Deeper Learning
    • Deeper RNNs
    • Bidirectional RNNs
  • Enterprise grade frameworks/frontend
    • spaCy
    • pytorch
    • Heroku
  • Incorporate third-party metrics
    • Spotify Web API popularity and sentiment metrics
    • RYM chart lists
